        "summary":  "The article argues that trustworthy AI agents for site reliability engineering require strict guardrails, human oversight, and grounded observability rather than full autonomy. It outlines five trust pillars ΓÇö grounded observability, clear guardrails, human-in-the-loop design, explainability, and real incident evaluation ΓÇö as prerequisites for team adoption. The author recommends architecturally separating reasoning from actuation to reduce operational risk in production environments.",
        "execSummary":  "This practitioner guide on SRE AI agent trust is directly applicable to any enterprise deploying autonomous agents in high-stakes operational contexts ΓÇö the five trust pillars are a deployable framework, not just theory. The most actionable insight for enterprise leaders is the architectural separation of reasoning from actuation: agents should be able to think and recommend without being able to act unilaterally, which preserves human control at the critical decision point. Earning team trust is as important as technical capability ΓÇö agents that fail opaquely destroy confidence and get switched off, while agents that fail transparently can be improved and kept in service. Organizations should adopt a trust ladder approach: start agents in observe-and-recommend mode, measure their accuracy, and grant actuation privileges only after demonstrating reliable judgment.",
